Crimée and Sudetenland, same fight?
BRUXELLES – The Russian takeover of Crimea constitutes the most serious example of aggression during peacetime that Europe has experienced since the annexation of the Sudetenland by Nazi Germany in 1938.
It is certainly now customary to downplay the importance of the "Munich lessons" when referring to this episode in which Neville Chamberlain and Édouard Daladier acceded to Hitler's claims on Czechoslovakia in order to calm the Führer.
Nonetheless, if the Western world were to turn a blind eye to Crimea's annexation – the second case of invasion of a sovereign territory by Russian President Vladimir Putin, following the occupation of the Georgian regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia in 2008 – current democratic leaders could very well regret their inaction.
Within Western capitals, reactions have so far been mixed.
The sanctions currently under consideration – such as expulsion from the G8, for example – could be seen as humorous if the threat to peace in Europe were not so serious.
Putin considers the collapse of the Soviet Union as the most serious catastrophe of modern times, an man relentlessly striving to resurrect a fallen Russian empire.
If the West is to be taken seriously, it will have to act with the same determination that Putin displays.
The numerous successes of the Russian president within the framework of his imperialist project have so far cost him almost nothing.
His initiative in favor of an Eurasian Economic Community has allowed Russia to attract a number of resource-rich states, such as Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan.
Georgia was partitioned in 2008.
As for the Armenian government, Russian intimidation pushed it to reject the association agreement proposed by the European Union.
And here is the most precious geopolitical trophy – Ukraine – which may well fall into Putin's hands.
Without Ukraine, Russia « ceases to be an empire, » as explains the former U.S. national security advisor Zbigniew Brzezinski; « on the other hand, strong with a corrupted and subordinate Ukraine, Russia automatically becomes an empire again. » And since the majority of Ukrainians do not at all aspire to join Putin's empire, it is very likely that the country led by the Russian president will now be a highly militarized state, a sort of Soviet Union without a Communist Party.
It is essential that the international community's reaction be up to the level of the adventurism that Putin is displaying.
Cancellation of summits, proposals for trade agreements and other participation in as unproductive forums as the G8 could never be sufficient.
Only actions involving the imposition of tangible economic sanctions, capable of affecting Russian citizens – who, we should recall, keep re-electing Putin to power – will allow us to hope that the Kremlin will abandon its expansionist trajectory.
What kind of sanctions could be involved?
First of all, Turkey could decide to close the Dardanelles Strait to Russian transport, as it did after the 2008 Russo-Georgian war.
At the time, Turkey had blocked access to the Black Sea in order to prevent the United States from intervening, although it now clearly appears that this was not the intention of the United States.
Today, Turkey could choose to close the Turkish straits not only to Russian warships, but also to all commercial vessels heading to Russian ports in the Black Sea.
The impact on Russia's economy – as well as on Putin's military ambitions – would be considerable.
Turkey is authorized to close the Dardanelles under an amendment made in 1982 to the 1936 Montreux Convention.
Turkey could thus turn the argument used by Putin to justify the annexation of Crimea – namely that he was preserving the ethnic Russians living there – by asserting that it itself is protecting its Turkic relatives of Tatar descent, who clearly wish to remain under Ukrainian rule due to the mistreatment they have suffered at the hands of Russia.
This week, Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoğlu ordered his plane to make a mid-air U-turn in order to head to Kiev to support the new interim government.
Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, who as Poutine knows is not exactly a softie either, could thus follow suit by immediately closing the Turkish straits to Russian transport – until Poutine withdraws all his troops from Crimea so that they can return to their bases, namely those of Sevastopol or Russia.
It would be good if Turkey could count on the guarantee conferred by Article 5 of the NATO treaty in the event that Russia attempts to intimidate it.
Secondly, President Barack Obama could impose on Russia the same type of financial sanctions that he imposed on Iran around its nuclear program.
These sanctions have indeed significantly undermined the Iranian economy.
In the same way, refusing access to the US financial system to all banks dealing with Russian banks or companies would generate an unprecedented economic chaos in Russia since the fall of communism.
Russian citizens must understand that allowing Putin – whose rise to power is based on his promise to end the shortages of the early post-Soviet era – to continue his aggressive imperialist course could cost them dearly.
Thirdly, Obama could remind the Chinese of their role in the stability of Eurasia.
To Putin, the disintegration of the Soviet Union was a true tragedy, but for China, it represented the most formidable geostrategic opportunity imaginable.
In an instant, this empire that had seized millions of hectares of Chinese territory over the centuries, and threatened the People's Republic with nuclear annihilation, simply vanished.
Since then, the independent states of Central Asia, and Ukraine itself, have become important trading partners for China.
The Russian invasion of Georgia seriously upset China, as evidenced by the Shanghai Cooperation Organisation summit held after the war (this regional grouping bringing together a number of post-Soviet states with common borders with China and the motherland).
Russia tried to persuade the OCS to recognize the independence of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
The Organisation nevertheless expressed its disagreement.
However, the Central Asian member states – Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan – would never have been able to rise against the Kremlin without China's support.
It is now up to President Xi Jinping of China to be less enigmatic in his response to Putin's audacity.
The real test of this Chinese claim to assert itself as a genuine and responsible protagonist within the international community will soon take place at the United Nations.
Will China support this blatant violation of international law committed by Putin, or will it stand in support of Ukraine's territorial integrity?
Two other sanction options are also under consideration.
Each Russian leader could thus see their visas denied or revoked.
It would also be possible to freeze a number of assets, including those that have been laundered by oligarchs close to Putin.
It is only when the pain becomes unbearable, especially for the elites, that this kind of kampf that Putin is leading today could fail.
The cost of inaction could turn out to be considerable.
Many countries, from Japan to Israel, rely on this American promise to act firmly against any serious threat to peace.
Moreover, when Ukraine gave up its nuclear arsenal in 1994, it did so under the condition that the United States (together with the United Kingdom, France, and Russia) guarantee its territorial integrity.
If Crimea were to remain annexed, no one could blame Ukraine if it decided to re-nuclearize its defense (something it remains technologically capable of doing).
When Chamberlain returned from Munich, Winston Churchill addressed him with the famous formula « You had the choice between war and dishonor.
You chose dishonor, and you will have war. » Obama and the other Western leaders are today facing a similar choice.
If they were to choose the dishonor, we can be certain that the audacious Putin will eventually serve them a new war.
